Charges for vehicle release: appeals
	The Private Security Industry Act 2001 is amended as follows.
	Before section 23 there is inserted—
	“22ACharges for vehicle release: appeals
		The Secretary of State shall by regulations make provision for the purposespecified in subsection (2) in a case where, in England and Wales or NorthernIreland, a person carries out—
			an activity to which paragraph 3 of Schedule 2 applies by virtue of sub-paragraph (1)(c) of that paragraph (demanding or collecting a charge as acondition of the removal of an immobilisation device); or
			an activity to which paragraph 3A of Schedule 2 applies by virtue of sub-paragraph (1)(d) of that paragraph (demanding or collecting a charge as acondition of the release of a vehicle).
		The purpose referred to in subsection (1) is to entitle a person otherwiseentitled to remove the vehicle to appeal against the charge.
		Regulations under this section shall specify the grounds on which an appealmay be made.
		The grounds may include in particular—
			contravention of a code of practice issued by the Authority;
			contravention of any requirement imposed by or under this Act (including acondition contained in a licence granted under this Act).
		Regulations under this section shall make provision for and in connectionwith the person to whom an appeal may be made.
		That person may in particular be—
			a person exercising functions of adjudication or the hearing of appealsunder another enactment;
			a body established by the Secretary of State under the regulations;
			an individual appointed under the regulations by the Secretary of State orby another person specified in the regulations.
		Regulations under this section may also include provision—
			as to the procedural conditions to be satisfied by a person before anappeal may be made;
			as to the payment of a fee by the appellant;
			as to the procedure (including time limits) for making an appeal;
			as to the procedure for deciding an appeal;
			as to the payment to the appellant by the respondent of—
			the charge against which the appeal is made;
			other costs incurred by the appellant in consequence of the activityreferred to in subsection (1);
			as to the payment by a party to an appeal of—
			costs of the other party in relation to the adjudication;
			other costs in respect of the adjudication;
			as to the payment by the respondent to an appeal, in a case where theappeal is granted, of a charge in respect of the costs of adjudications underthe regulations;
			as to the effect and enforcement of a decision of the person to whom anappeal is made;
			requiring or authorising the person to whom an appeal is made to provideinformation relating to the appeal to the Authority;
			to the effect that a person who makes a representation that is false in amaterial particular, and does so recklessly or knowing it to be false, commitsan offence triable summarily and punishable with a fine not exceeding level 5on the standard scale.
		The provision specified in paragraphs (e), (f) and (g) of subsection (7)includes provision authorising the person to whom an appeal is made to requirepayment of the matters specified in those paragraphs.”
		In section 24 (orders and regulations), in subsection (4), after “section3(2)(j)” there is inserted “or 22A”.

Prison security
	Offences relating to electronic communications devices in prison
		In the Prison Act 1952, in section 40D (other offences relating to prisonsecurity)—
			in subsection (1)(b), for “or any sound” there is substituted “, sound orinformation”;
			in subsection (3), paragraph (b) and the preceding “or” are repealed;
			after subsection (3) there is inserted—
			“(3A)A person who, without authorisation, is in possession of any of the itemsspecified in subsection (3B) inside a prison is guilty of an offence.
			(3B)The items referred to in subsection (3A) are—
			a device capable of transmitting or receiving images, sounds or informationby electronic communications (including a mobile telephone);
			a component part of such a device;
			an article designed or adapted for use with such a device (including anydisk, film or other separate article on which images, sounds or informationmay be recorded).”
